and improved quality of life. However, this study has several limitations. First, the sample size was small, which may affect the generalizability of the results. Larger multicenter studies are needed to validate our findings. Second, the patients were from a single institution, potentially causing selection bias. Third, the NRS relied on for pain assessment may introduce subjective variability in reporting. Future research should address these issues to confirm the combined intervention’s efficacy and safety in broader clinical settings. Publisher’s Note Springer Nature remains neutral with regard to jurisdictional claims in published maps and institutional affiliations. Authors’ contributions Tongqiang Cai designed the study, and made data analysis and interpretation. Meixia Li drafted and reviewed the manuscript. Qingxia Yan revised manuscript. All the authors of this study read and approved the final manuscript. Funding The authors declare that no funds, grants, or other financial support were received from any public, commercial, or not-for-profit entities for the conduct of this research, the preparation of this manuscript, or the decision to submit it for publication. All authors confirm that there are no financial or non-financial conflicts of interest related to this work. Data availability The data that support the findings of this study are available from the corresponding author, MX L, upon reasonable request. Declarations Ethics approval and consent to participate The research plan and data collection have been reviewed and approved by the Ethics Committee of Dujiangyan People’s Hospital. (No. LW-2024-03-02). Consent for publication All patients included in the study have signed informed consent forms. Written informed consent was obtained from a legally authorized representative(s) for anonymized patient information to be published in this article. Competing interests The authors declare no competing interests. References 1. Lin YZ Chen P Lin MM Explor